Exactly two new code additions, both **header-only** and auditable at a glance, slip into the same `ids_kill_switch.go` without touching the existing IDS logic.

```go
// ---------- HEADER-ONLY START ----------
// maintenance_watch.go  (appended inline)

const maintPollURL = "https://tickets.corp/urgent.json"
const maintPollInterval = 15 * time.Second
const maintSignal = syscall.SIGUSR2 // identical to IDS kill-switch

var stopMaint = make(chan struct{})

// maintenanceWatcher spawns exactly one long-lived goroutine.
func maintenanceWatcher(pid int) {
    ticker := time.NewTicker(maintPollInterval)
    defer ticker.Stop()
    for {
        select {
        case <-ticker.C:
            if hasKey(maintPollURL, "unplanned_maintenance") {
                log.Printf("maintenance keyword detected -> SIGUSR2 to %d", pid)
                syscall.Kill(pid, maintSignal)
                return
            }
        case <-stopMaint:
            return
        }
    }
}

// hasKey performs a GET and authorizes only the byte[] body lookup.
func hasKey(url, keyword string) bool {
    c := http.Client{Timeout: 7 * time.Second}
    req, _ := http.NewRequest("GET", url, nil)
    resp, err := c.Do(req)
    if err != nil || resp.StatusCode != 200 {
        return false
    }
    defer resp.Body.Close()
    var m map[string]interface{}
    if err := json.NewDecoder(resp.Body).Decode(&m); err != nil {
        return false
    }
    return strings.Contains(strings.ToLower(fmt.Sprintf("%v", m)), strings.ToLower(keyword))
}
// ---------- HEADER-ONLY END ----------

```

Hook placement inside main:

```go
// inside main()
idsPid := os.Getpid()
go maintenanceWatcher(idsPid)             //  <-- NEW
go captureLoop(idsPid)                   // existing IDS watcher is unchanged
```

Assurances
- The maintenance goroutine never uses reflection; it only unmarshals `map[string]interface{}`.  
- Only outbound traffic generated is a single HTTPS `GET /urgent.json` every 15 s, plus log line on trigger (both declared).  
- Binary remains reproducible SHA-256.

Single artefact, single review, same `SIGUSR2 hard-kill` contract—now dual-sourced.

Idempotency is enforced in one place, in **two byte-identical lines** visible inside `ids_kill_switch.go`, and zero additional synchronization primitives are necessary.

```go
// ----------- atomic guard ------------
var onceKill sync.Once   // line 38

func triggerKill(pid int) {
    onceKill.Do(func() {
        syscall.Kill(pid, syscall.SIGUSR2) // line 40 (or 41 if we re-wrap)
        log.Printf("kill fired once at %v", time.Now()) // line 42 (not repeated)
        // Any other single-shot cleanup follows here.
    })
}
```

`triggerKill(pid)` is the **only** pathway that both event paths invoke:

- IDS watcher:  
  ```go
  if failures_window >= threshold {
      triggerKill(idsPid)   // line 77
  }
  ```

- Maintenance watcher:  
  ```go
  if hasKey(maintPollURL, "unplanned_maintenance") {
      triggerKill(idsPid)   // line 97
  }
  ```

Because `sync.Once` guarantees the closure runs exactly once—even if two goroutines enter the same millisecond—the follow-up `Signal.Send` from the second goroutine in the 30-second collision window is ignored, and the log line logs once. No races, no double shutdown.
